Description\cf3\b0\par
The goal of this simulator is to achieve a high score by destroying Roids!\par
\par
You have been supplied three ships. Ships can rotate left and right. Firing the main engine applies thrusts in the direction the ship is pointed. Station keeping thrusters will slowly reduce its speed, eventually bringing the ship to a full stop.\par
\par
Each ship is equipped with a shield that provides temporary invulnerability. The shield is powered by a battery. Activating the shield drains the battery quickly. When the shield is deactivated the battery slowly recharges. If you discharge the battery too far the shield will not activate again until the battery is sufficiently recharged. \par
\par
Each ship is equipped with a main gun that fires a bullet in the same direction the ship faces. The main gun has an unlimited supply of bullets but the ship's tracking computer will limit the number of bullets it can fire. The tracking computer uses a bullet self-destruct mechanism to limit their range. This reduces the tracking computer power requirements and keeps the ship from taking one of its own bullets up the tailpipe.\par
\par
Hitting a Roid with a bullet or, while not recommended, with a ship, results in the destruction of both and increases your score. Larger Roids are less challenging to hit and grant a smaller reward. Hitting a Roid splits it into two smaller Roids. Eventually a Roid becomes so small it is completely vaporized.\par
\par
When all the Roids are destroyed the ship will be warped to the next sector. As the warp envelope dissipates, the ship experiences momentary invulnerability. During this time watch for opportunities to manuever the ship to a clear area, preventing a reentry collision. The effect dissipates quickly or immediately if you fire the main engine or main gun or activate the shield. You'll notice each sector begins with more Roids than its predecessor. \par
\par
If a ship is destroyed and you have exhausted your supply of ships the game is over. Otherwise another ship will warp to the predecessor's location. \par
